    "<div style=\"background: #0d2137; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid #1f6feb; margin-top: 20px;\">\n",
    "  <h3 style=\"color: #79c0ff; margin-top: 0;\">Chapter 8 — Key Takeaways</h3>\n",
    "  <ul style=\"color: #c9d1d9; line-height: 1.8; margin: 12px 0 16px 0;\">\n",
    "    <li><strong>REINFORCE</strong> uses no baseline, needs no extra network, and is the simplest policy-gradient method, but it has high variance and is therefore the most unstable.</li>\n",
    "    <li><strong>REINFORCE + Baseline</strong> subtracts a learned value estimate $V(s)$, adds a separate value network, and usually gives strong variance reduction with medium residual variance.</li>\n",
    "    <li><strong>RLOO (K=4)</strong> uses the empirical leave-one-out mean as a free baseline, requires no extra network, and works well in batched setups with low-to-medium variance.</li>\n",
    "  </ul>\n",
    "\n",
    "  <p style=\"color: #c9d1d9; line-height: 1.8; margin: 0;\">\n",
    "    <strong style=\"color: #f0a500;\">Key insight:</strong> The policy gradient remains <strong>unbiased</strong> regardless of baseline choice. Baselines reduce <strong>variance</strong>, not bias, which makes training more stable.\n",
    "  </p>\n",
    "</div>\n",
